Copy Data to multiple devices for 
- Fault Tolerance 
- High avaailabilty 
- High Scalability

Data replication can be achieved through 
leader-based push or pull mechanisms where a leader propagates changes to followers, 
or through leaderless approaches where clients write to multiple replicas and consistency is maintained via versioning and repair. 
The choice depends on trade-offs between throughput, latency, and consistency.

Core Models 
1) Leader-Follower Push based 

    Client → Leader → Leader writes → Leader pushes updates → Followers → Followers apply changes
    
    Leader sends 
      WAL (Write Ahead Log)
      Row changes

    Latency           Medium        Wait for push
    Throughput        Medium        Leader does extra work
    Consistency       Strong        Leader controls replication 
    Availability      Medium        Leader is bottleneck

    OptimisedFor      Strong control and consistency 
    Cost              Leader bottleneck, Scaling limited 
    

2) Leader-Follower Pull based

    Client → Leader → append log 
    Followers → “give me data after offset X” → pull data → append locally
    
    Followers request missing data
    Leader just serves log
    
    Latency           Medium        Depends on polling
    Throughput        High        Leader doesn’t push
    Consistency       Depends       Followers may lag
    Availability      High          Followers control speed
  
    OptimisedFor      High throughput and Scalability 
    Cost              Replica lag & Slightly weaker consistency



3) Leaderless Multi-Writer

    No Single leader
  
    Client → Node A, Node B, Node C (replicas)
    Client → Node A → forwards to B, C
  
    Application client
    DB client library
    Coordinator node
    Proxy Server
  
    Each node stores data independently
    Versioning added
    Repair fixes inconsistencies later

    Latency           Low              No coordination
    Throughput        Very High        Parallel writes
    Consistency       Eventual         Conflicts possible
    Availability      Very High        No single point
  
    OptimisedFor      Availability & multi-region 
    Cost              Conflict resolution & Complexity


4) Log Shipping (WAL)

    Leader → write WAL → send WAL to followers → followers replay WAL

    Latency           Medium           
    Throughput        High             Sequential log
    Consistency       Strong           Exact replay
  
    OptimisedFor      Exact replication
    Cost              Replay delay & Tight coupling

5) Snapshot + Incremental Sync

    New node joins → Copy full snapshot → Then apply logs incrementally

    Latency           High initially     Full copy    
    Throughput        Medium             Heavy data transfer
    Consistency       Strong             Syncs fully
  
    OptimisedFor      Bootstrapping new nodes
    Cost              Expensive initial sync

